<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n03164e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03164e">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03164e"> 164(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> wedding favors white heather / &amp; myrtle <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03164e"><li>FW 504.36-505.01 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n03164e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n03164e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03164e">MS BL 47482b-97v</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:066 <a name="rA2yd" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rA2yd">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/r/rA2yd.htm#n03164e">Draft: III&sect;3A.2+</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: The wedding dress of the later Queen Elisabeth, who married on 26 April 1923, was described in these words: &lsquo;The veil, of antique lace, was secured by <mark>a simple bandeau of myrtle leaves, with a knot of white roses of York and white heather at each ear</mark>. It was lent to the bride by her future mother-in-law, Queen Mary. Lace played a significant part in weddings and these heirlooms were passed from mother to daughter (or daughter-in-law) for their special dresses.&rsquo; </mm> </dd></dl>
